    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>The Audience Isn't Listening</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Karen G Krueger letter about Mar 25 article on computerized music on Broadway wonders whether people can tell difference between live and computer-generated sound (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Artificial sound may not, in all cases and to all ears, be worse than natural sound, but it is different. I prefer the unamplified human voice and the sound of instruments directly heard and felt. I have chosen not to attend Broadway musicals in recent years because I hate the sound they now present. (I go to classical music concerts.) But I wonder how many are no longer able to hear the difference between natural and machine-generated sound. Will my opportunities to hear unmediated music be curtailed for lack of an audience that really hears?</p>
        <p>Karen G. Krueger  Manhattan</p>
      </block>
